{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff94f513-e445-43c9-ba01-68d26c5a2452","content":"No repo to inspect, so here's the general guidance:\n\n## Migrating from VSTest@3 → Microsoft.Testing.Platform\n\n### 1. Update your test project\n\nIn each test `.csproj`, add:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nThis makes each test project a self-contained executable using Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\n### 2. Replace VSTest@3 with `dotnet test`\n\nReplace:\n\n```yaml\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**\\*Tests.dll'\n    resultsFolder: $(Agent.TempDirectory)\\TestResults\n```\n\nWith:\n\n```yaml\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration $(BuildConfiguration)\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --logger \"trx;LogFileName=TestResults.trx\"\n      --collect \"Code Coverage;Format=Cobertura\"\n```\n\n### 3. Publish results & coverage\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish test results'\n  condition: succeededOrFailed()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish code coverage'\n  condition: succeededOrFailed()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/coverage.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Concern | VSTest@3 | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|---|\n| Runner | `vstest.console.exe` | Built into test executable |\n| Invocation | Matches built DLLs | `dotnet test` on `.csproj` |\n| TRX reports | Built-in | `--logger trx` flag |\n| Code coverage | Built-in collector | `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` |\n\nThe `--logger trx` and `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` flags replace what VSTest@3 did automatically. Use `condition: succeededOrFailed()` on publish steps so results are reported even on test failure.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5cb52d3f-15a8-4e9f-a406-b3cda1ce2dc7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is a general question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure Pipelines. I can answer this from my knowledge.","outputTokens":659,"requestId":"5C39:184190:AAEA7:D605C:69F54B27"},"id":"25fc6110-b279-4fa5-b7a9-1c122a2640a3","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:54:12.131Z","parentId":"481191f4-7da2-480b-ad5b-c9e0c7701f5a"}
